    \th{Good idea }
    \th{Bad idea }
    \th{Another bad idea}
  }
  \tr{
    \td{The idea }
    \td{The world is \em{out there}. }
    \td{The truth is \em{out there}. }
    \td{Nothing is \em{out there}.}
  }
  \tr{
    \td{Explanation }
    \td{The world is not our creation; most things in space and time do not have human mental states as causes.  Without sentences there is no truth, human languages are human creations. \em{Descriptions} of the world are not out there,[^sen] and only those can be true or false.}
    \td{There are objectively better or worse ways to describe the world. There is a best way (e.g. perhaps fundamental physics); the world splits itself up into sentence-shaped chunks called 'facts'. Sentences are true or false by relating to those facts. }
    \td{The world \em{is} our creation; it is constructed out of our thoughts or social practices.}
  }
  \tr{
    \td{Truth and representationalism }
    \td{Truth is made; languages are made, and truth is a property of linguistic entities. }
    \td{Truth is found; truth represents the world, and the world is not made by us. }
    \td{Truth is found; truth represents the world, and the world is made by us.}
  }
  \tr{
